It was about half the room, so let's do just a real quick overview of just kind of a history

00:02:15.300 --> 00:02:21.779
of why I became passionate about community college education.

00:02:21.779 --> 00:02:27.139
Why is this such a big deal?

00:02:27.139 --> 00:02:33.020
There are over a thousand community colleges in the United States.

00:02:33.020 --> 00:02:44.460
That's a map of them, made in R. Only 20 of them, maybe more, maybe a few more, we

00:02:44.460 --> 00:02:50.259
keep adding a couple every year, but it's under 20 that actually have a program right

00:02:50.259 --> 00:02:55.899
now, whether it's a certificate or an associate's degree or something, that's either called

00:02:55.899 --> 00:02:59.460
data science or data analytics.

00:02:59.460 --> 00:03:07.899
Compared to the over a thousand, we have a little bit of a ways to go.

00:03:07.899 --> 00:03:15.419
As a comparison, we did not make this graph in R. This is copied off of a report that

00:03:15.419 --> 00:03:21.740
was put out by the government, but compared two-year to four-year colleges, we have about

00:03:21.740 --> 00:03:32.539
36% of all students who were undergraduates in the year 2016, 36% were in two-year colleges,

00:03:32.539 --> 00:03:37.300
which is more than a third, and it's kind of surprising to hear that number.

00:03:37.300 --> 00:03:41.940
Most people think that it's not quite that much, because we think about all the undergraduate

00:03:41.940 --> 00:03:49.059
colleges out there, you're like, well, it can't be, but it is.

00:03:49.059 --> 00:04:00.699
As far as the numbers of students who receive bachelor's degrees, I think this was 2015-16.

00:04:00.699 --> 00:04:08.779
Of all the bachelor's degrees awarded in that year, 49% of those students had started out

00:04:08.779 --> 00:04:16.540
at a community college, 49%, almost half.

00:04:16.540 --> 00:04:18.299
State by state, it does differ.

00:04:18.299 --> 00:04:26.420
The highest percentage is Texas, where we are right now, at 75%.

00:04:26.420 --> 00:04:30.820
They're really pushing community college education.

00:04:30.820 --> 00:04:34.739
The lowest is Rhode Island, 24%.

00:04:34.739 --> 00:04:39.540
You can barely see it there, but it's there.

00:04:39.540 --> 00:04:43.660
Why did I become passionate about this?

00:04:43.660 --> 00:04:52.019
Because what happens is a student comes out of high school, and even adults who might

00:04:52.019 --> 00:04:57.339
want to go back for a credential, but especially high school students, let's focus on them

00:04:57.339 --> 00:04:59.339
for a second.

00:04:59.339 --> 00:05:03.660
They start out at a community college, and they get a list of programs that they could

00:05:03.660 --> 00:05:07.100
sign up for.

00:05:07.100 --> 00:05:13.140
Very few of them, or not many of them, are really comfortable with math or science.

00:05:13.140 --> 00:05:18.260
You have few engineering people who just are determined to do engineering.

00:05:18.260 --> 00:05:23.179
That's kind of a unique crowd.

00:05:23.179 --> 00:05:27.339
Most students pick a program, and then they sort of stick with that.

00:05:27.339 --> 00:05:33.140
They're not going to diverge from that, hence the road.

00:05:33.140 --> 00:05:39.700
What I would like to see is I would like to see more students exposed to data science

00:05:39.899 --> 00:05:45.739
in the community college setting, so that then when they transfer to a four-year college,

00:05:45.739 --> 00:05:52.619
they're sort of on a track to continue that kind of work, and maybe do research-driven

00:05:52.619 --> 00:06:02.899
work, and maybe choose a STEM major.

